{
  "style": "IEEE",
  "texts": [
    "Within the confines of a learning task defined by humans, the deep neural networks (DNNs) at the heart of GenAI systems must be sufficiently flexible to learn whatever there is to learn-that is the point of machine learning.",
    "Weights and biases are not hand-tuned by humans, and while humans write training algorithms and build system architectures, they do not fully determine what a system learns in particular (e.g.",
    "which representations), especially in unsupervised or self-supervised regimes.",
    "So, while GenAI systems are not independent in the sense of 'choosing to do it their own way', and what they end up learning is still importantly shaped by human aims, leadership and oversight [4,58], we maintain that GenAI systems can nevertheless exhibit some forms of independence if what they learn and later draw on at inference is not fully determined by humans.",
    "DirectnessFinally, directness captures how directly a contribution is involved in producing an output."
  ],
  "correct_citations": [
    "So, while GenAI systems are not independent in the sense of 'choosing to do it their own way', and what they end up learning is still importantly shaped by human aims, leadership and oversight [4,58], we maintain that GenAI systems can nevertheless exhibit some forms of independence if what they learn and later draw on at inference is not fully determined by humans."
